> Maybe something to keep in mind: If we went with different metatables to carry additional information, the raw table {x, y} could be passed without conversion as argument to functions that take a tuple as a parameter.


It would allow to use `unpack` on a `Position`, which would enable composition with all (0, 0) based functions. An example:


```lua
local p1 = vim.pos({4, 1})
vim.inspect_pos(0, unpack(p1))
vim.show_pos(0, unpack(p1))
```

I know some here are not a fan of too much OO style or metatables, but I think for position and range it is very tempting to implement some. For example:

```lua
---@class vim.Position (0,0) indexed (line, column) tuple
local Position = {}

local position_mt = {
  __index = Position,
  __tostring = function(x)
    return "(" .. x[1] .. ", " .. x[2] .. ")"
  end,
  __eq = function(a, b)
    return a[1] == b[1] and a[2] == b[2]
  end,
  __lt = function(a, b)
    return a[1] < b[1] or (a[1] == b[1] and a[2] < b[2])
  end,
  __le = function(a, b)
    return a[1] <= b[1] or (a[1] == b[1] and a[2] <= b[2])
  end,
}

---@param position string|integer[]
---@return vim.Position
function M.pos(position)
  local pos
  if type(position) == "string" then
    -- [bufnum, lnum, col, off]; 1-indexed
    pos = vim.fn.getpos(position)
    pos = { pos[2] - 1, pos[3] - 1}
  else
    pos = position
  end
  return setmetatable(pos, position_mt)
end
```

Would make things like the `normalize` trivial:

```lua
---@class vim.Range
local Range = {}

local range_mt = {
  __index = Range,
  __tostring = function(range)
    return tostring(range[1]) .. ", " .. tostring(range[2])
  end
}

function Range:normalize()
  if self[1] > self[2] then
    return setmetatable({self[2], self[1]}, range_mt)
  else
    return self
  end
end

function Range:text(bufnr)
  local lines = api.nvim_buf_get_text(bufnr, self[1][1], self[1][2], self[2][1], self[2][2] + 1, {})
  return table.concat(lines, "\n")
end
```

We could also enable conversion from `(0, 0)` to `(1, 1)` indexing with just `p1 + 1`, or to go from `(0, 0)` to `(1, 0)` it could support `p1 + {1, 0}`
